<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n34006g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n34" href="#n34006g">N34 (VI.B.27)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n34all.htm#n34006g"> 6(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lauras / (hermitage)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">K. Lake &hellip; traces the development through three well-defined stages in the 9th and 10th centuries&mdash;&nbsp;(a) the hermit period,&nbsp;(b) the loose organization of <mark>hermits in lauras</mark>,&nbsp;(c) the stricter rule of the monastery, with definite buildings and fixed rules under an &hellip; abbot. The monasteries now have taken over the name lauras. They are under the jurisdiction of the metropolitan; a few of the most important deal direct with the patriarch and are called <i>Stauropegia</i>. <small> &ldquo;ORTHODOX EASTERN CHURCH&rdquo; <a name="EBOEC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBOEC"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 336 [Monastic Life]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
